<br>
Here is what I think.  I am one of the people who does not like Crylin, but I also don't really think what he did was ban worthy.  Reading your description of why he was banned, I can see why he was.  I guess I am sort of measuring Crylin and Kwip by the same scale simply because all this went down at the same time.  I see what Crylin does to be annyoing and self serving, but what Kwip does is more aggressive, threatening and truly disrupting a large section of the forum.<br>
<br>
I do support the idea of some bans being temporary.  Obviously I think there are some people who should just remain banned, SZ trolls etc.  But if it is someone who is a legitimate part of the community and they want to try to pull themselves together, I think they should have that chance.<br>
<br>
Now, all that being said, I do not think they should have indefinate chances. Using Kwip as an example, he was banned and given two more chances after that first ban to stay on as a regular forum member.  He ended both chances with threats, spamming and telling the mods essentially it didn't matter what rules they placed on him.<br>
<br>
I am all for giving people a chance to fly right, but I also believe some people are just going to behave a certain way, either because of age or environment.  And eventually they have to take responsibility for their actions.<br>
<br>
As much as I support the idea of second chances, I think it can be problematic.  I honestly do trust our mods to handle these situations as they come, but I think some sort of guideline would help the ban process actually carry some weight.  Right now bans look like something A) We wont ever use or B) If we do use it, you get to come back anyways.<br>
I think there should be some stability in this rule.<br>
<br>
